Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – The invasion of Ukraine by Russia on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given carte blanche to Putin to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider his confirmation as leader for life in China later in the year a mere formality.
After concentrating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he would be raised to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin undertook to realize his dream with incredible brutality.
Approaching his 70th birthday, Putin thinks that if he wants to impose his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it's a vision that distorts the 'soul' of Russia, emotional to the point of sentimentality.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned they were willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you ask them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tian'anmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have observed his rise from very close up, being aware of his cruelty.
He has reduced to nothing the Chechen capital, Grozny. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB operator, but he seems to have changed lately.
Having developed an idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He has certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome the Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be just as positioned as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have put up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems to be able to stop nothing.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians were misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
Mais dans the second part, it's Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians have fought bravely during the 2014 'Euromaidan protests.
The 2014 events plunged him into a black rage.
But the Russian army made a poor showing when it received the order to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The corruption rooted in defense contract allocation also played an important role in its insufficient results.
However, instead of beating himself up, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without meeting the slightest resistance.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and ignores all the rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing the civilian population.
Many hospitals have been hit and the power grid feeding the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia may well be losing the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive arms to Ukraine and efforts are underway to buy Soviet-made MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already achieved wonders in strengthening the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is going it alone.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remains 'solid', Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say he supported their efforts to restore peace.
He wanted to express maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will accede to Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be ousted before they destroy our civilization.
